<subSubSection id="2CDE41C4F5443F254B0CE8D0F946C8DD" pageId="72" pageNumber="83">
<paragraph id="647B124FF5443F254B0CE8D0F9E6C870" blockId="72.[300,1699,1616,2492]" pageId="72" pageNumber="83">
The 
<typeStatus id="BB7FACEDF5443F254BA0E8D0FD8CC68B" box="[448,616,1976,2019]" pageId="72" pageNumber="83">paratypes</typeStatus>
show some color variation, there being reddish flecks around the eyes in some specimens, an occasional reddish tinge on the scutellum, and a suggestion of brown subapically on hind femora. The brown of the lateral margins, of pronotum extends over onto a portion of the propleura. The most distinctive feature of this species, other than the male genitalia, is the red central area of hemelytra with contrasting ochraceous across the middle of clavi. This is a common species on 
<collectingCountry id="1CD352DFF5443F25495AE786FC46C870" box="[826,930,2286,2328]" name="Guam" pageId="72" pageNumber="83">Guam</collectingCountry>
and is obviously not host specific.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="647B124FF5443F254B0BE64CF946C8DD" blockId="72.[300,1699,1616,2492]" pageId="72" pageNumber="83">
<taxonomicName id="A3C469CCF5443F254B0BE64CFDDCC826" authorityName="Usinger" authorityYear="1946" box="[363,568,2340,2382]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Aretas" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="72" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="signatus">
<emphasis id="56B0CE5DF5443F254B0BE64CFDDCC826" box="[363,568,2340,2382]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="83">A. signatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
will run to 
<emphasis id="56B0CE5DF5443F254977E64CFC60C826" box="[791,900,2340,2382]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="83">flavus</emphasis>
Knight or 
<emphasis id="56B0CE5DF5443F254E37E64CFADCC826" box="[1111,1336,2340,2382]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="83">iniperatorius</emphasis>
Distant in Knight's key (B. P. Bishop Mus., Bull. 
<emphasis id="56B0CE5DF5443F254900E63FFC7DC8E9" bold="true" box="[864,921,2391,2433]" pageId="72" pageNumber="83">142:</emphasis>
167, 1937) but does not agree with these or any other described species in color or in shape of male ge~ital claspers.
</paragraph>
